On the other hand the ashy grape and the dusky grape and the donkey—grapea are condemned even by their appearance, though this is less the case with the alopecis,⁶ which resembles a fox's brush. A grape growing in the vicinity of Phalacra is called the Alexandrian grape ; it is a low-growing vine with branches only eighteen inches long and a black grape the size of a bean, with a soft and very small stone3 the clusters hang aslant and are extremely sweet 3 the leaf is small and round, and has no clefts. Within the last seven years there has been discovered at Viviers in the province of Narbonne a vine whose blossoms wither in a day and which is consequently extremely immune to bad weather3 it is called the ‘ charcoal- vine,’ and is now grown by the whole province.
